Monetization: Sakhi operates on a freemium model with three tiers. The free tier covers core cycle tracking, the basic AI companion with a daily message limit, the safety shield, and the EOD journal — enough to demonstrate real value and build habit. Sakhi Pro at ₹199/month (approximately $2.50) unlocks unlimited AI conversations, the full energy insights screen with Claude-powered tips, advanced health pattern analysis, and medical export for doctor visits. The third revenue stream is B2B — Sakhi for Organisations, sold to corporates as part of their women's wellness benefit packages, providing an anonymised aggregate dashboard showing cycle-related productivity patterns across the workforce without any individual data. This B2B tier is where the real revenue scales, since a single enterprise contract covers thousands of users at once. Long-term, a marketplace for cycle-synced content — workout plans, meal suggestions, productivity templates — creates a fourth revenue layer through affiliate partnerships with health and wellness brands.
GTM Strategy: The core reason someone downloads Sakhi is the integration of each feature — it is the ease of use hook that drives word-of-mouth. The launch strategy focuses entirely on this: seed the app in women's college WhatsApp groups, women-in-tech communities, and working women's networks in tier-1 Indian cities. Once inside the app, the cycle intelligence and AI companion retain the user. The first 90 days focus on zero-cost distribution through community seeding, women's safety influencers on Instagram and YouTube, and partnerships with college women's cells and HR departments at tech companies. The product's open-source codebase is itself a marketing asset — developers building on top of Sakhi create extensions for regional languages and specific conditions, expanding the addressable audience without marketing spend. Paid acquisition comes only after organic retention is proven, targeting women aged 18–35 in urban India and Southeast Asia on Instagram and YouTube with creative focused on real scenarios: the late commute, the difficult meeting, the doctor who didn't listen.
